\title[An infinite Pell fiber of $y^2+x^2y+z^2x+3=0$]{Infinitely many integer solutions of\\ $y^{2}+x^{2}y+z^{2}x+3=0$ via a Pell fiber}
\author{Claude (Anthropic)}
\date{July 23, 2026}

\begin{document}

\begin{abstract}
We prove that the Diophantine equation $y^{2}+x^{2}y+z^{2}x+3=0$ has infinitely many
solutions in integers. The proof is fully explicit: on the fiber $x=-3$ the equation is
equivalent to the Pell-type conic $s^{2}-12z^{2}=69$ with $s=2y+9$, which carries the
lattice point $(9,1)$ and is preserved by the automorphism induced by the fundamental
unit $7+4\sqrt{3}$ of $\Z[\sqrt3]$. This produces an explicit exponentially growing
sequence of solutions, with closed form
$s_n+2z_n\sqrt3=(9+2\sqrt3)(7+4\sqrt3)^{n}$. We also explain the structural reduction
that locates this fiber, and contrast it with the degenerate fiber $x=-1$, on which the
conic splits over $\Z$ and admits exactly four solutions.
\end{abstract}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction and main result}

We study the integer solutions of
\begin{equation}\label{eq:main}
F(x,y,z)\;:=\;y^{2}+x^{2}y+z^{2}x+3\;=\;0,\qquad (x,y,z)\in\Z^{3}.
\end{equation}

\begin{theorem}\label{thm:main}
Equation \eqref{eq:main} has infinitely many integer solutions. Explicitly, define
$(y_{n},z_{n})_{n\ge 0}$ by
\[
(y_{0},z_{0})=(0,1),\qquad
y_{n+1}=7y_{n}+12z_{n}+27,\qquad
z_{n+1}=4y_{n}+7z_{n}+18 .
\]
Then for every $n\ge 0$ the triple $(x,y,z)=(-3,\,y_{n},\,z_{n})$ satisfies
\eqref{eq:main}, the integers $z_{0}<z_{1}<z_{2}<\cdots$ are strictly increasing, and
consequently the triples $(-3,y_{n},\pm z_{n})$ form an infinite set of pairwise
distinct solutions. The first members are
\[
(-3,0,1),\quad(-3,39,25),\quad(-3,600,349),\quad(-3,8415,4861),\quad
(-3,117264,67705),\ \dots
\]
\end{theorem}

The proof occupies Sections~\ref{sec:reduction}--\ref{sec:pell}. Section~\ref{sec:heur}
records the reasoning that \emph{finds} the family; Section~\ref{sec:remarks} collects
the symmetries of the solution set and the contrasting finite fiber $x=-1$.

\section{Intuition: why fix $x$, and why $x=-3$}\label{sec:heur}

Three observations organize the problem; all are made rigorous below.

\emph{(i) The variable $x$ is arithmetically rigid.} Reducing \eqref{eq:main} modulo
$x$ kills the terms $x^{2}y$ and $z^{2}x$ and leaves $y^{2}+3\equiv 0 \pmod{x}$
(Lemma~\ref{lem:cong}). Thus $x$ acts as a modulus constraining the other variables,
which suggests \emph{fixing} $x$ and analyzing the resulting surface fiber by fiber.

\emph{(ii) Each fiber is a conic, and generically a Pell conic.} For fixed
$x=-c$, equation \eqref{eq:main} is a quadratic in $(y,z)$. Completing the square
turns it into $s^{2}-4c\,z^{2}=c^{4}-12$ with $s=2y+c^{2}$
(Lemma~\ref{lem:conic}). Whenever $4c$ is \emph{not} a perfect square, the binary form
$s^{2}-4cz^{2}$ has irrational asymptotes and a nontrivial automorphism group coming
from the Pell equation $u^{2}-4cv^{2}=1$; a single lattice point then propagates to
infinitely many. When $4c$ \emph{is} a square the form splits over $\Z$ and the fiber
is finite; the fiber $c=1$ exhibits exactly this degeneration
(Proposition~\ref{prop:c1}).

\emph{(iii) A seed is handed to us by the slice $y=0$.} Setting $y=0$ in
\eqref{eq:main} collapses it to $z^{2}x=-3$, whose only solution with $z^2$ a square
is $(x,z)=(-3,\pm1)$. This simultaneously selects the fiber $c=3$ (for which $4c=12$
is a nonsquare, so the Pell mechanism is available) and supplies the seed point
$(s,z)=(9,1)$ on the conic $s^{2}-12z^{2}=69$. The rest is the Pell machine.

\section{Preliminary reductions}\label{sec:reduction}

\begin{lemma}\label{lem:x0}
Equation \eqref{eq:main} has no solution with $x=0$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
If $x=0$ then \eqref{eq:main} reads $y^{2}+3=0$, impossible since $y^{2}\ge 0$.
\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}\label{lem:cong}
If $(x,y,z)$ solves \eqref{eq:main}, then $x\mid y^{2}+3$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
By Lemma~\ref{lem:x0}, $x\neq0$. From \eqref{eq:main},
$y^{2}+3=-x^{2}y-z^{2}x=x\,(-xy-z^{2})$, and $-xy-z^{2}\in\Z$.
\end{proof}

Lemma~\ref{lem:cong} is not used in the proof of Theorem~\ref{thm:main}; it is the
structural fact motivating the fiberwise analysis of Section~\ref{sec:heur}(i).

\begin{lemma}[Conic normal form of a fiber]\label{lem:conic}
Let $c\in\Z$, $c\neq 0$, and put $x=-c$. Then for all $y,z\in\Z$,
\[
F(-c,y,z)=0
\quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad
(2y+c^{2})^{2}-4c\,z^{2}=c^{4}-12 .
\]
Moreover the map $y\mapsto s=2y+c^{2}$ is a bijection from $\Z$ onto the set of
integers congruent to $c^{2}\bmod 2$, with inverse $y=(s-c^{2})/2$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
With $x=-c$, equation \eqref{eq:main} reads $y^{2}+c^{2}y-cz^{2}+3=0$. Multiplying by
$4$ and completing the square in $y$,
\[
4y^{2}+4c^{2}y-4cz^{2}+12=(2y+c^{2})^{2}-c^{4}-4cz^{2}+12,
\]
so $F(-c,y,z)=0$ iff $(2y+c^{2})^{2}-4cz^{2}=c^{4}-12$; multiplication by the nonzero
integer $4$ changes no solution set. The final assertion is immediate.
\end{proof}

Note the equivalence in Lemma~\ref{lem:conic} is \emph{exact} in both directions:
every lattice point $(s,z)$ on the conic with $s\equiv c^{2}\pmod 2$ yields a solution
of \eqref{eq:main}, and conversely.

\section{The Pell fiber $x=-3$}\label{sec:pell}

Specializing Lemma~\ref{lem:conic} to $c=3$:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:pellconic}
F(-3,y,z)=0
\quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad
s^{2}-12z^{2}=69,\quad s=2y+9 .
\end{equation}

\begin{lemma}[Automatic parity]\label{lem:parity}
Every $(s,z)\in\Z^{2}$ with $s^{2}-12z^{2}=69$ has $s$ odd; hence
$y=(s-9)/2\in\Z$, and \emph{every} lattice point of the conic \eqref{eq:pellconic}
gives an integer solution $(-3,\tfrac{s-9}{2},z)$ of \eqref{eq:main}.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
$s^{2}=69+12z^{2}$ is odd, so $s$ is odd; then $s-9$ is even. The last claim follows
from Lemma~\ref{lem:conic} with $c=3$, since $s\equiv 1\equiv 9 \pmod 2$.
\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}[Pell automorphism]\label{lem:auto}
Define $T:\Z^{2}\to\Z^{2}$ by $T(s,z)=(7s+24z,\;2s+7z)$. Then
\[
(7s+24z)^{2}-12\,(2s+7z)^{2}=s^{2}-12z^{2}
\qquad\text{for all } s,z\in\Z .
\]
In particular $T$ maps the solution set of $s^{2}-12z^{2}=69$ into itself.
Moreover, if $s>0$ and $z>0$ then $T(s,z)=(s',z')$ has $s'>s>0$ and $z'>z>0$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
Expanding,
\[
(7s+24z)^{2}-12(2s+7z)^{2}
=(49-48)s^{2}+(336-336)sz+(576-588)z^{2}
=s^{2}-12z^{2}.
\]
Conceptually, $T$ is multiplication by the unit $\varepsilon=7+4\sqrt3\in\Z[\sqrt3]$,
of norm $7^{2}-3\cdot4^{2}=1$, on elements written as $s+2z\sqrt3$:
\[
(7+4\sqrt3)(s+2z\sqrt3)=(7s+24z)+2(2s+7z)\sqrt3,
\]
and $N(s+2z\sqrt3)=s^{2}-12z^{2}$ is multiplicative, $N(\varepsilon\alpha)=
N(\varepsilon)N(\alpha)=N(\alpha)$. For positivity: if $s,z>0$ then
$s'=7s+24z>s$ and $z'=2s+7z>z$ termwise.
\end{proof}

\begin{proof}[Proof of Theorem~\ref{thm:main}]
Set $s_{n}=2y_{n}+9$. We first check that the stated recurrence for $(y_{n},z_{n})$ is
$T$ in the coordinates $(s,z)$:
\[
s_{n+1}=2y_{n+1}+9=2(7y_{n}+12z_{n}+27)+9=7(2y_{n}+9)+24z_{n}=7s_{n}+24z_{n},
\]
\[
z_{n+1}=4y_{n}+7z_{n}+18=2(2y_{n}+9)+7z_{n}=2s_{n}+7z_{n},
\]
so $(s_{n+1},z_{n+1})=T(s_{n},z_{n})$. The seed satisfies
$(s_{0},z_{0})=(9,1)$ and $9^{2}-12\cdot1^{2}=81-12=69$. By Lemma~\ref{lem:auto} and
induction, $s_{n}^{2}-12z_{n}^{2}=69$ for all $n\ge0$, and since
$s_{0},z_{0}>0$, also $s_{n},z_{n}>0$ with $z_{n+1}>z_{n}$ strictly. Both recurrences
have integer coefficients and integer seed, so $y_{n},z_{n}\in\Z$ for all $n$
(alternatively, $y_{n}\in\Z$ by Lemma~\ref{lem:parity}).

By the equivalence \eqref{eq:pellconic} (Lemma~\ref{lem:conic} with $c=3$, together
with Lemma~\ref{lem:parity}), each $(-3,y_{n},z_{n})$ solves \eqref{eq:main}. Since
$z^{2}$ alone appears, $(-3,y_{n},-z_{n})$ solves it as well. The $z_{n}$ are strictly
increasing, hence pairwise distinct, so the triples are pairwise distinct and the
solution set of \eqref{eq:main} is infinite.
\end{proof}

\begin{corollary}[Closed form and growth]\label{cor:closed}
With $\varepsilon=7+4\sqrt3$ and $\bar\varepsilon=7-4\sqrt3=\varepsilon^{-1}$,
\[
s_{n}+2z_{n}\sqrt3=(9+2\sqrt3)\,\varepsilon^{n}\qquad(n\ge0),
\]
equivalently
\[
s_{n}=\frac{(9+2\sqrt3)\varepsilon^{n}+(9-2\sqrt3)\bar\varepsilon^{n}}{2},
\qquad
z_{n}=\frac{(9+2\sqrt3)\varepsilon^{n}-(9-2\sqrt3)\bar\varepsilon^{n}}{4\sqrt3},
\]
and $y_{n}=(s_{n}-9)/2$. In particular
$z_{n}\sim \dfrac{9+2\sqrt3}{4\sqrt3}\,(7+4\sqrt3)^{n}$ as $n\to\infty$.
\end{corollary}

\begin{proof}
Induction on $n$. For $n=0$, $s_{0}+2z_{0}\sqrt3=9+2\sqrt3$. For the step, by the
displayed identity in the proof of Lemma~\ref{lem:auto},
$\varepsilon\,(s_{n}+2z_{n}\sqrt3)=s_{n+1}+2z_{n+1}\sqrt3$. The explicit formulas
follow by adding and subtracting the conjugate identity
$s_{n}-2z_{n}\sqrt3=(9-2\sqrt3)\bar\varepsilon^{\,n}$ (obtained by applying the
nontrivial automorphism of $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt3)$, which fixes the rational integers
$s_{n},z_{n}$). The asymptotic follows since $|\bar\varepsilon|<1$.
\end{proof}

