\section{Symmetries, sporadic solutions, and the split fiber $x=-1$}\label{sec:remarks}

\begin{remark}[Symmetries of the solution set]
Since $z$ enters \eqref{eq:main} only through $z^{2}$, the map $z\mapsto -z$ preserves
solutions. On a fixed fiber $x=-c$ there is additionally the Vieta involution
$y\mapsto -c^{2}-y$ (i.e.\ $s\mapsto -s$), because $y$ and $-c^{2}-y$ are the two
roots of the quadratic $Y^{2}+c^{2}Y+(3-cz^{2})$. For $c=3$ this sends the family of
Theorem~\ref{thm:main} to a second infinite family $(-3,\,-9-y_{n},\,\pm z_{n})$,
e.g.\ $(-3,-9,\pm1)$ and $(-3,-48,\pm25)$.
\end{remark}

\begin{proposition}[The fiber $x=-1$ is finite]\label{prop:c1}
The solutions of \eqref{eq:main} with $x=-1$ are exactly
$(-1,2,\pm3)$ and $(-1,-3,\pm3)$.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
By Lemma~\ref{lem:conic} with $c=1$: $F(-1,y,z)=0$ iff $s^{2}-4z^{2}=-11$ with
$s=2y+1$. Here $4c=4$ is a perfect square and the form factors over $\Z$:
$(s-2z)(s+2z)=-11$. Write $a=s-2z$, $b=s+2z$, so $ab=-11$ and, since $11$ is prime,
$(a,b)\in\{(1,-11),(-1,11),(11,-1),(-11,1)\}$. In each case $s=(a+b)/2$ and
$z=(b-a)/4$ must be integers; all four cases pass, giving
$(s,z)\in\{(-5,-3),(5,3),(5,-3),(-5,3)\}$, i.e.\ $s=\pm5$, $z=\pm3$. Then
$y=(s-1)/2\in\{2,-3\}$, and one checks directly that all four resulting triples
satisfy \eqref{eq:main}: $4+2-9+3=0$ and $9-3-9+3=0$.
\end{proof}

Proposition~\ref{prop:c1} is the precise sense in which the Pell mechanism can fail:
when $4c$ is a square the conic degenerates into a pair of rational lines and admits
only the finitely many lattice points dictated by the divisors of $c^{4}-12$. The
choice $c=3$ in Theorem~\ref{thm:main} is the smallest fiber that is both
nondegenerate ($12\notin\Z^{2}$) and \emph{populated}, the seed being supplied by the
slice $y=0$ of \eqref{eq:main}: $y=0$ forces $z^{2}x=-3$, whence $x=-3$, $z=\pm1$
(the alternative $x=-1$, $z^{2}=3$ being impossible).

\begin{remark}[Other sporadic solutions]
The slice $z=0$ also yields solutions, though only finitely many on that slice:
\eqref{eq:main} becomes $y(y+x^{2})=-3$, so $y\mid 3$; checking
$y\in\{\pm1,\pm3\}$ gives exactly $(\pm2,-1,0)$ and $(\pm2,-3,0)$. These lie on the
fibers $x=\pm2$ and are unrelated to the infinite family above; they illustrate that
the full solution set of \eqref{eq:main} is a union of fiberwise conic loci of varying
richness. A complete classification of \emph{all} solutions would require deciding,
for every $c$ with $4c$ nonsquare, whether the Pell-type equation
$s^{2}-4cz^{2}=c^{4}-12$ is soluble --- a genuinely fiber-by-fiber question that we do
not pursue, Theorem~\ref{thm:main} already settling the dichotomy posed
(``finitely many, listed, or provably infinitely many'') in favor of infinitude.
\end{remark}

